ce:section.ce:para:
Film and bulk xerogel samples were characterized by means of FTIR and Raman spectroscopy (Fig. 2
                        ), in order to understand if the cross-linking process occurred differently in the two systems. In the figure, peak assignment was done on the basis of Refs. [10,11,15,16] and [17]. No major differences were observed in peak positions, indicating that both film and bulk matrices present the same structure. The main difference between the two types of samples can however be noticed in the intensity of the broad band of FTIR spectrum (Fig. 2a), ranging from 2500cm−1 to 3600cm−1 and from 1500cm−1 to 1800cm−1. These FTIR bands can be attributed to the presence of NH3
                        + −HCO3 groups formed, during silane hydrolysis, from the interaction of NH2 terminal groups of the trialkoxysilane with water and carbon dioxide from atmosphere [10,11,18]. This attribution is further confirmed by the results of a simple experiment, hereafter described, whose results are visible in the spectra reported in the inset of Fig. 2a (enlarged 1800–1500cm−1 region). Bulk AEAP-TMOS samples have been produced as described before and immediately analyzed after drying in the oven at 60°C for 3days. Then, they were again measured after storage in air for 10days. As it can be observed, the band at about 1600cm−1, present in the AEAP-TMOS precursor spectrum and ascribed to NH bending vibration of primary amines, turns out split in two components: a weaker one at about 1650cm−1 and a more intense one at about 1570cm−1. On the other hand, the NH2 peak at about 1600cm−1 is visible in the spectrum of the as-dried sample, whereas after air exposure for several days this component is absent, thus indicating the completion of the reaction with carbonic acid formed by interaction of atmospheric CO2 and moisture. To confirm the hypothesis that an ammonium hydrogen carbonate salt has formed as a result of air exposure, a sample of pure liquid AEAP-TMOS was added with a drop of glacial acetic acid and the spectrum was immediately collected. As it can be seen in Fig. 2a (inset), the appearance of the two components ascribed to (NH3)+ ion at 1650cm−1 (asymmetric NH bending) and 1570cm−1 (symmetric NH bending) is clearly detected, thereby confirming the bands assignment mentioned above. The lower intensities of these bands in thin film spectra can be explained by assuming that, during the spin-coating deposition, the evaporation of water and solvents occurs much faster than in monolithic samples, thus leading to pore collapsing and microcavity contraction. On the other hand, in monolithic samples a highly porous network is allowed to form, owing to the slow evaporation of water and solvent concomitant with cross-linking progress, so that trapping of moist air and solvent in larger sites is promoted and amine conversion to ammonium ion and hydrogen carbonate can take place [19].
